<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08091f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08091f">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08091f"> 91(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mental nerve (chin)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[I]</font>n a great many cases it is really contrary to the genius of the language to use an adjective at all. &hellip; but physiologists think it more dignified to speak of the <i>gustatory nerve</i> than of the <i>taste nerve</i> and will even say <i>mental nerve</i> (Lat. mentum &lsquo;chin&rsquo;) instead of <i>chin nerve</i> in spite of the unavoidable confusion with the familiar adjective <i>mental</i>. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 131 [Adjectives]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
